 to the turn of the twentieth century. Organized along a careful genealogy of ballads in the Atlantic world, The Social Lives of Poems in Nineteenth-Century America demonstrates how the circulation of texts in songs, broadsides, letters, and newsprint as well as in books, anthologies, and critical essays enabled poetry to perform its many different tasks. Considering the media and modes of reading through which people encountered and made sense of poems, Cohen traces the lines of critical interpretations and tracks the emergence and disappearance of poetic genres in American literary culture. Examining well-known works by John Greenleaf Whittier and Walt Whitman as well as popular ballads, minstrel songs, and spirituals, Cohen shows how discourses on poetry served as sites for debates over history, literary culture, citizenship, and racial identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAmerican poetryy19th centuryxHistory and criticismxHistoryy19th century. 0aAmerican poetryy19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican poetry. 0aBooks and readingxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aBooks and readingxSocial aspects. 0aLiterature and societyzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th centuryy19th century. 0aLiterature and societyzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aLiterature and society. 0aPoetryxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aPoetryxSocial aspects. 4aCultural Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aLiterature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2015z9783110438673oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Penns